ive impact of this radically new theory of responsibility in understandings of industrial hazards, in manufacturing dangers, and in the stories that were told and retold about accidents. In exciting tales of the actions of "good Samaritans" or of sea, steamboat, or railroad accidents, features of risk that might otherwise escape our attention--such as the suddenness of impact, the encounter between strangers, and the debates over blame and responsibility--were reconstructed in a manner that revealed both imagined and actual solutions to one of the most difficult philosophical and social conflicts in the nineteenth-century United States. Through literary and legal stories of accidents, Goodman suggests, we learn a great deal about what Americans thought about blame, injury, and individual responsibility in one of the most formative periods of our history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAccident lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAccidents in literature. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBlame in literature. 0aLaw and literaturexHistoryy19th century. 0aLegal stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aNegligence in literature. 0aResponsibility in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAdams, Henry.  aArmstrong, John.  aBanta, Martha.  aBercovitch, Sacvan.  aBlumin, Stuart.  aBoorstin, Daniel.  aCardozo, Benjamin.  aCole, John.  aCover, Robert.  aCrane, Stephen.  aDane, Nathan.  aDeVoto, Bernard.  aDimock, Wai Chee.  aEisenberg, Melvin Aron.  aFiss, Owen.  aFlanders, Henry.  aFreud, Sigmund.  aFriedman, Lawrence.  aGallagher, Catherine.  aGiedion, Siegfried.  aGoldberg, Reuben Lucius.  aGoodrich, Peter.  aHacking, Ian.  aHarr, Jonathan.  aHeisenberg, Werner.  aHorwitz, Howard.  aHowells,